data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already threw `InvalidOperationException` for synchronous LINQ by default, but you could opt back in via the sync-over-async shim (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`). **In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every synchronous call against the Cosmos provider now throws with no workaround.

### Affected calls in your code

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(…)` | `.FirstAsync(…)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migration

Convert the repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This means `async/await` must propagate up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.). The `Add()` call itself remains synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; the actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
